Bitcoin 2025 - Las Vegas: The Battle For Bitcoin's Soul (Analyst Takeaways)

Dylan Bane
Sam Ruskin
Armita

Jun 4, 2025   19 min read

Going into Bitcoin Vegas, Bitcoin surged past its all-time high, hitting a record $111,970 on May 22.

Bitcoin Vegas made clear the catalysts driving BTCs momentum. Nation states like Pakistan are announcing strategic Bitcoin reserves. Public companies with mediocre growth prospects are pivoting toward MicroStrategy-style holding companies. The Vice President announced at the conference that digital assets and particularly Bitcoin, are part of the mainstream economy, and are here to stay. Even the Presidents eldest sons gave price targets live on stage, predicting BTC could clear $170,000 by the end of next year.

However, beneath the headlines, an underlying tension could be felt at the conference. In contrast to the narrative of institutional adoption driving BTC forward, most attendees appeared to be retail holders and fans of BTC, not industry professionals. While conferences like ETH Denver and Token2049 are dominated by those building products, Bitcoin Vegas reflected that the core of Bitcoin is still the everyday holder.

Amid this tension, the fundamental question of Bitcoin's purpose and role in the world returns with more importance than ever. What started as a trustless P2P electronic payment system is now a multitrillion-dollar digital store of value, with its sights on flipping golds global market cap. How is the Bitcoin community adapting to Bitcoins commanding march onto the world stage?

Bitcoin Vegas arrives at a critical juncture in Bitcoins path.

  • How will Bitcoin respond to the proliferation of stablecoins?
  • Do nation states and Wall Street giants holding Bitcoin undermine its original vision as a revolutionary alternative to a broken financial system?
  • Will bringing DeFi, smart contracts, and programmability to Bitcoin position it as the settlement layer for all of crypto or threaten Bitcoins narrative as a simple digital store of value?

Perhaps most importantly, is all of this activity window dressing? At its core, is Bitcoin more than a pure speculative instrument? Does the decision to hold Bitcoin 2026 again next year in Las Vegas, the global capital of gambling, say something about Bitcoin's essence?

Messari analysts in attendance at Bitcoin Vegas 2025 grapple with these questions below, as the battle for Bitcoins soul ramps up.

A Rather Political Affair by Dylan

Last year, then-candidate Donald Trump headlined Bitcoin Nashville with a series of sweeping promises: pardoning Ross Ulbricht, removing SEC Chair Gary Gensler, and establishing a Strategic Bitcoin Reserve. Following his election in November, markets responded immediately. Bitcoin surged to all-time highs, and the AI-agent narrative took center stage for onchain traders. The cycles speculative peak came with the launch of the Official Trump memecoin, which reached a fully diluted valuation of over $80 billion within days of launch.

However, the first 90 days of the Trump presidency delivered a sharp correction in digital asset markets. This drop came despite the administration following through on its core crypto commitments. Ross Ulbricht was pardoned. A national strategic Bitcoin reserve and digital asset stockpile were announced. Gensler resigned before Trump took office, and pro-crypto figures like Hester Peirce assumed leading roles in a restructured SEC. The prevailing explanation for the downturn was that markets had priced in overly ambitious expectations for policy shifts. Meanwhile, initially unclear tariff policy uncertainty introduced macro volatility that suppressed risk appetite.

By mid-April, however, market sentiment reversed. Bitcoin rallied to new highs ahead of Bitcoin Vegas as regulatory clarity firmed and trade tensions stabilized. Entering the conference, there was clear momentum and a shared sense that the administration's crypto-friendly posture could solidify into long-term policy.

The centerpiece of Bitcoin Vegas was Vice President J.D. Vances keynote on the Nakamoto Stage. Hundreds were shut out of the room as the crowd rushed in to get a sense of the Administrations current stance on crypto and Bitcoin.

Vance set the tone directly: Crypto finally has a champion and an ally in the White House. His remarks addressed a wide range of themes: the convergence of AI and crypto, stablecoin accessibility via the administration-backed GENIUS Act, and a vision of the U.S. as a global leader in digital asset policy.

The subtext of the speech was forward-looking. Vance appeared to position himself not just as a steward of the current administrations digital asset strategy, but as a potential successor who would carry that agenda forward. The result was a renewed sense of directional certainty for U.S. crypto regulation through at least 2028.

Later that afternoon, Donald Trump Jr. and Eric Trump joined the leadership team of American Bitcoin (ABTC) on stage. The panel underscored the Trump familys deepening commitment to the crypto economy. Donald Jr. made it clear that crypto has become central to their business strategy, stating, Were very long crypto. Its a huge part of everything we do now. Eric Trump, taking aim at legacy finance, added, I would love to see some of the big banks go extinct, because honestly, they deserve it. While the rhetoric was hyperbolic in the typical Trumpian manner, the underlying message was consistent: the Trump family is materially and ideologically aligned with Bitcoin.

On the business front, the Trump Media & Technology Group announced a $2.5 billion purchase of Bitcoin. The Trumps also detailed their new venture, American Bitcoin, which aims to mine BTC below market cost (estimated at $40,000-$60,000 per Bitcoin) and hold it on the balance sheet. Both initiatives mirror Michael Saylors Strategy playbook, using public companies to issue debt, which is then used to build Bitcoin treasury positions and extract NAV premiums. Combined with their exposure to World Liberty Financial and the Official Trump memecoin, the familys fortunes are now structurally intertwined with the crypto economy, reaffirming that their interest in crypto extends beyond politics.

Internationally, momentum for strategic Bitcoin adoption continued to build. Pakistans Minister of State for Blockchain and Crypto, Bilal Bin Saqib, announced a national Bitcoin reserve along with plans to dedicate 2,000 megawatts of surplus energy to BTC mining infrastructure. In the UK, Reform Party leader Nigel Farage unveiled similar plans for a Bitcoin reserve should his party take power. He also proposed tax and banking reforms aimed at making the UK a friendlier jurisdiction for crypto entrepreneurs. With the U.S. taking a leadership role, the dominoes for state-level Bitcoin adoption appear to be falling.

One of the most emotionally charged moments of the conference came with the onstage appearance of Ross Ulbricht. Pardoned only four months earlier from a double life sentence, Ulbrichts return was met with a standing ovation. For many in the community, he remains a symbol of Bitcoins founding values. With so much speed and chaos, its more important than ever to stay true to our principles, he said, naming freedom, decentralization, and unity as Bitcoins core pillars.

As political, financial, and cultural forces increasingly converge around Bitcoin, Bitcoin Vegas 2025 may be remembered as the first major event to showcase this new alignment. But Ulbrichts presence served as a reminder that Bitcoins legitimacy does not come from institutions; it comes from its principles and code. Whether those principles endure in the next phase of adoption remains an open question.

The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly by Sam

Bitcoin 2025 was supposed to be a checkpoint for the ecosystem, a moment to assess where the worlds largest crypto asset is heading. In some ways, it delivered. The energy was palpable. The venue was full. We reflected on how far we had come in the past 4 years of hardship. But for those tracking technical and infrastructural progress, the signal was murky. Important breakthroughs like Bitcoin rollups, trust-minimized execution, and growing demand for Bitcoin productivity were largely overshadowed by political theater. That imbalance might seem benign now, but it raises deeper questions about how this ecosystem sustains itself beyond 2028.

The Good: Bitcoins Programmable Foundation Is Forming

Underneath the noise, Bitcoins technical trajectory is quietly accelerating. Rollups, side systems, and L2s have moved from vaporware to functioning prototypes. TVL in Bitcoin-native DeFi is up 12X in the past year, despite limited functionality. The appetite for programmable Bitcoin is clear, not just among developers, but among capital allocators as well. BTCFi has graduated from a speculative meme to an investable vertical, even if most of the infrastructure remains in early innings.

The primary constraint remains unchanged: bridging. Without a secure, trust-minimized way to move BTC between layers, the system remains fractured. Multiple approaches are in development, including BitVM2 and OP_CAT, but none are production-ready. Until then, BTC remains functionally siloed.

Still, the groundwork is being laid. Expect narrative momentum around Bitcoin rollups and trust-minimized bridging to build over the next 1218 months, especially as protocols like Citrea, Botanix, Arch, and Alpen launch their mainnet. If ~$10B TVL exists today on top of rudimentary DeFi infrastructure, the growth curve is steep once composability and capital efficiency arrive.

The Bad: Bitcoin is stuck as Political Capital

While the builders were present, the spotlight belonged to the politicians. Bitcoin 2025 leaned heavily into its role as a political rally. Trump-aligned figures dominated the discourse. Eric Trump and Don Jr. were stacking sats, and JD Vance declared Trump Bitcoins champion.

The politics werent subtle. But the concern isnt the messaging: its the imbalance. Bitcoins credibility used to come from its neutrality. Thats shifting now that the U.S. election cycle is part of cryptos fundamental narrative, and Bitcoin is increasingly a pawn in more concentrated ideological games. This might work in the short term, but it creates a long-term dependency. What happens when the champion exits the arena?

A cycle defined by political capital instead of technical capital is one step closer to stagnation. If this doesnt feel urgent now, revisit this thought in 3.5 years.

The Ugly: Bitcoin Crypto

If you came to Bitcoin 2025 expecting optimism for the future of non-Bitcoin crypto, you were likely disappointed. Despite crypto-native builders and investors attending, the divide between Bitcoin and the rest of the industry felt wider than ever.

Theres no obligation for Bitcoin to absorb the rest of crypto, but there could be a cost to this isolation. As capital consolidates in a few assets, the future for altcoins looks grim. For Bitcoin L2s, this could be a nice tailwind. Theres an abundance of locked-up capital for them to vamp. But for Ethereum and Solana apps, the culture issue will eventually become a capital issue. When attention fragments and capital inflow stalls, bridging talent and research becomes harder, and the gap widens.

Cryptos trajectory isnt locked in. Ethereum and Solana still dominate DeFi, structurally and in mindshare. But momentum is shifting. Leadership today doesnt guarantee leadership tomorrow.

The Political Convergence of Bitcoin and Conservatism by Armita

While the main stages at Bitcoin 2025 featured major speeches and panels, some of the most revealing conversations took place in the Whale Lounge: a reserved area for institutional investors, founders, and high-net-worth attendees. The lounge provided a quieter setting for informal discussions with speakers and industry leaders, becoming a place where political ambition and Bitcoin advocacy often intersected. It underscored Bitcoins expanding role in broader economic and policy discourse.

Political Signaling and Bitcoin Advocacy

Saylor, in turn, positioned Bitcoin not just as a financial asset, but as a cultural and ideological movement. Calling it the orange movement, he likened Bitcoin to a peaceful revolution rooted in individual sovereignty and economic independence. He argued that Bitcoin offers states a way to preserve long-term economic stability and align themselves with a future defined by digital value. The conversation underscored how deeply intertwined Bitcoin has become with emerging political identities and policy platforms.

Bitcoin as a Response to Financial Censorship

Following that discussion, Eric Trump shared his personal journey into the crypto space, describing the early backlash and skepticism he faced when he first voiced support for Bitcoin. He spoke about his familys experience with being debanked, losing access to traditional financial services, and explained that this played a major role in steering them toward Bitcoin. He framed it as a response not just to exclusion, but to a broader distrust of the traditional banking system. Trump emphasized that his family is now fully committed to the movement, viewing their support for Bitcoin as both a practical necessity and an ideological stance.

Bitcoin's Long-Term Monetary Thesis

The next day, TV host and economic commentator Mark Moss joined a panel alongside other speakers, including James Lavish and Lawrence Lepard, to present a broad narrative around Bitcoins long-term role in the global financial system. The conversation focused on Bitcoins fixed supply and predictable issuance schedule, which were framed as foundational to its appeal in a world of monetary expansion and fiat currency debasement. It was discussed that these characteristics make Bitcoin uniquely positioned to appreciate structurally over time, assuming continued demand growth.

Another theme was the notion of a dual reserve standard, where Bitcoin and gold serve as complementary hedges in an increasingly unstable monetary environment. It was noted that while gold dominated similar conversations during previous political cycles, particularly under the earlier Trump administration, Bitcoin now appears to be taking center stage in both policy discussions and investor portfolios.

From Holding to Building

The Bitcoin Opportunity Fund was also briefly highlighted as part of this broader conversation. Framed as a new initiative to channel capital into Bitcoin-native infrastructure and early-stage ventures, the fund was discussed in the context of rising institutional interest in not just holding BTC, but building around it. This includes investments in mining operations, energy infrastructure, and adjacent technologies that enhance Bitcoins role as a long-term strategic asset. The panel suggested that this marks a shift toward viewing Bitcoin not only as a financial instrument but as a catalyst for innovation in power markets and digital infrastructure.

As a personal takeaway, this reflects Bitcoins growing intersection with the emerging DePIN (Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks) sector. Traditionally viewed as just a digital asset or monetary instrument, Bitcoin is now increasingly tied to real-world infrastructure, particularly through mining. Bitcoin mining operations require physical hardware, stable energy sources, and often custom-built facilities, making them a clear example of decentralized infrastructure in action.

With initiatives like the Bitcoin Opportunity Fund investing in energy systems, mining facilities, and supporting technologies, it's clear that Bitcoin's future extends beyond financial speculation. It now plays a role in shaping decentralized compute and energy networks, key pillars of the DePIN thesis, where value accrual and network security are directly linked to physical resource coordination.

Metaplanet: Asias Bitcoin-Treasury Pioneer

A notable session featured the team from Metaplanet, often referred to as "Japans MicroStrategy" for its bold Bitcoin treasury strategy. The company outlined its approach to accumulating Bitcoin as a core balance sheet asset, including the use of debt instruments, such as zero-interest bonds, to finance its BTC purchases. As of their latest disclosure, Metaplanet has acquired over 8,888 BTC. While they are not yet among the top global corporate holders, their strategy has positioned them as a leading Bitcoin-adopting public company in Asia and a potential long-term player in corporate Bitcoin adoption.

Bitcoin 2025 was not only a showcase for high-profile speeches but also a window into the increasingly tight relationship between Bitcoin, politics, infrastructure, and ideology. Beyond the main stage, discussions in the Whale Lounge revealed how Bitcoin is evolving from an asset class into a foundation for new political identities, economic strategies, and decentralized infrastructure investments

Lending & Leverage as a Double-Edged Sword by Austin and Mohamed

BTC Las Vegas was easily one of the most thought-provoking crypto conferences this year. The energy was high, the panels were bold, and the attendees, ranging from protocol founders to institutional reps, spoke with a confidence that suggested Bitcoins long-awaited adoption was finally here. Governments, banks, and large corporations are getting in. BTC is evolving quickly maybe even a bit too quickly for its own good.

But beneath the surface of this wave of institutional enthusiasm, theres a thorn that isnt getting enough attention: the rapid growth in BTC-backed lending and the increasingly aggressive use of leverage. These financial tools have become central to the narrative around Bitcoin as pristine collateral. However, when combined with a lack of transparency, they could introduce systemic risks that are all too familiar.

The MicroStrategy Problem


One of the most talked about moments of the conference was Michael Saylors response when asked if MicroStrategy would publish proof of reserves. Saylor dismissed the idea, stating that it was not a good idea, citing concerns over wallet traceability, security risks, and potential liability. His reasoning wasnt entirely without merit but it was far from reassuring.

Since 2020, MicroStrategy has taken on billions in debt to acquire over 580,000 BTC. Much of that debt is collateralized with Bitcoin, meaning price drawdowns can trigger margin calls or even forced liquidations if the company isn't adequately hedged. As of now, the firm holds over $8.0 billion in outstanding debt, and the average cost basis of its BTC is around $66,000, giving it a wide margin above water at current prices. But that margin is not immune to volatility, especially during sharp downturns or macro risk-off events.

Without public proof of reserves, investors and institutions are being asked to take Saylors word on faith for how much BTC is actually held, how much is encumbered, and what liquidity exists in the event of a crisis. Post FTX, this stance feels increasingly outdated, especially in a market that is slowly demanding institutional-grade transparency. The refusal to offer basic onchain verification raised fair questions throughout the conference:

  • Does MicroStrategy actually hold the BTC it claims?
  • How much is locked up as collateral or otherwise illiquid?
  • Could its liquidation have cascading impacts on the broader market?

While MicroStrategy is often celebrated for its aggressive BTC strategy, its lack of transparency sets a worrying precedent as more firms adopt similar treasury models. In a worst-case scenario, this could become the crypto version of too big to fail with no way for outsiders to measure the actual risk. Even if Microstrategy holds strong, which we all hope it does, amongst the firms that adopt similar treasury models or leveraged positions, some must fail, and such failure will only result in cascading effects in the BTC space as a whole.

BTC-Backed Lending

One of the clearest themes at BTC Las Vegas was the rapid rise of BTC-backed lending. It came up in nearly every conversation, whether with founders, investors, or traditional finance delegates. In one way or another, everyone seemed to be exploring how to unlock liquidity without selling BTC. While this reflects growing confidence in Bitcoins role as pristine collateral, it also highlights a shift from self-sovereign ideals to more financialized and potentially risk-laden infrastructure.

BTC-backed lending allows users to post BTC as collateral in exchange for loans in dollars or stablecoins. This strategy enables access to capital without triggering taxable events or losing long-term upside. But while the concept is simple, the implementation and the risks are becoming more complex.

Platforms like SALT Lending and Unchained Capital have long served retail borrowers, offering custodial and multi-sig options for BTC-backed loans. Meanwhile, Ledn provides institutional-style products with transparent terms, and YouHodler pushes LTV ratios as high as 97%, making it one of the more aggressive lenders in the market. Some platforms like Nexo offer near-zero percent interest rates for certain customers, provided the LTV and loyalty tiers align.

More recently, newer entrants have started bridging the gap between decentralized and traditional finance:

  • At the conference, Strike CEO Jack Mallers announced a new system for issuing BTC-backed loans directly through the Strike wallet. The product promises instant approvals and low interest rates, with no traditional credit checks required.
  • Coinbase partnered with DeFi protocol Morpho to offer United States users up to $100,000 in USDC backed by BTC.
  • Cantor Fitzgerald recently launched a $2.0 billion BTC-backed lending program, signaling Wall Streets growing involvement in crypto collateralized credit markets.
  • Rocko now acts as a DeFi aggregator, helping users source loans across platforms like Aave and Morpho.

This boom in lending options demonstrates Bitcoins continued maturation, but it also reintroduces familiar risks. In particular:

  • Volatility: BTC price drawdowns can quickly erode collateral, triggering mass liquidations and downward spirals.
  • Counterparty risk: Most lending remains custodial, meaning borrowers must trust platforms to safeguard BTC and remain solvent.
  • Transparency: Many loans are issued offchain, with limited visibility into collateralization ratios or systemic exposure.

There is still no standard method for verifying how much BTC is locked in loans or how much leverage exists across platforms. Without clear disclosures, the ecosystem remains vulnerable to stress events. It is difficult to know how exposed some borrowers or lenders might be, or how quickly market confidence could deteriorate in a downturn.

While lending unlocks utility and deepens financial integration, it also turns Bitcoin from a bearer asset into a credit instrument. That shift brings tradeoffs. As one panelist remarked during the event, in the name of liquidity, we might be giving up self-custody, and with it, one of Bitcoins core superpowers.

BTCs Wild West Is Not Over Yet

For many early Bitcoiners, this moment is surreal. The same asset once hailed as a tool of individual sovereignty is now being used by public companies to take on billions in corporate debt. It is being integrated into global fast food chains like Steak n Shake, whose Lightning integration reportedly slashed processing fees by 50%. It is even being used by governments for monetary policy experiments.

But with scale comes consequences. And if we are honest, no one really knows how this experiment ends.

Bitcoin has entered its institutional era, but that does not mean it has left the Wild West behind. Until we get real transparency standards for leveraged BTC positions and lending markets, this new wave of adoption will remain a double-edged sword, one that may cut deeper the longer we ignore it.

At the same time, there is reason for optimism. The growing involvement of major firms, banks, and global merchants signals that Bitcoin is finally being recognized not just as an investment but as financial infrastructure. The tools and practices being built now, from proof of reserves frameworks to improved custody models and real-time settlement rails, could help Bitcoin move beyond the chaos of its early years and into a more mature phase of adoption. The road ahead may be uneven, but the direction is clear: Bitcoin is no longer on the fringe. It is becoming part of the system, and with that comes an opportunity to shape how that system evolves.
